        {
            "id": "60133a8426ba4079980da",
            "questionText": "A water balloon is launched from a slingshot on flat ground at an angle of $!$\\theta = 60^{\\circ}!$ above the horizontal with an initial velocity of $!$u = 15 \\,m/s!$. Assuming negligible air resistance and a gravitational acceleration of $!$g = 9.81 \\, m/s^2!$, determine the magnitude of the water balloon's velocity at the instant when it reaches half of its maximum height above the ground.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "5aa7a2154bbc4420b11a8",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying which formula is used to calculate the maximum height of a projectile. Which formula correctly represents the calculation for $!$y_{max}$!$?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "db4469d3-56b0-4923-9df8-aa1377bb9e6b"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$y_{max} = \\frac{u^2 \\sin^2\\theta}{2g}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$y_{max} = \\frac{u^2 \\cos^2\\theta}{g}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$y_{max} = \\frac{u \\sin\\theta}{g}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "53d7956efba24281abbe3",
                    "stepText": "Great. Now, using the chosen formula and the provided values $!$u = 15 \\,m/s$!$, $!$\\theta = 60^\\circ$!$, and $!$g = 9.81 \\,m/s^2$!$, calculate the maximum height reached by the water balloon. (Round to one decimal place.)",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "8.6"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "db4469d3-56b0-4923-9df8-aa1377bb9e6b"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "0e3a071165e947cf9450d",
                    "stepText": "Now, find half of this maximum height. What is the value of $!$\\frac{y_{max}}{2}$!$?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "4.3"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "0c9dcf2e49d04909a3a09",
                    "stepText": "Next, we need to break the initial velocity into its horizontal and vertical components. To start, which formula should be used to determine the horizontal component $!$u_x$!$?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "6549c13e-d336-4760-899a-1964b1b38828"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$u_x = u \\cos{\\theta}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$u_x = u \\sin{\\theta}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$u_x = u \\tan{\\theta}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "c7bd6e96f7b1487680d57",
                    "stepText": "Using the appropriate formula, calculate the horizontal component of the initial velocity with $!$u = 15 \\,m/s$!$ and $!$\\theta = 60^\\circ$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
